{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12477"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.17,0.05,0.37,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48911"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4984"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1843"},{"type":"tags","id":"1865"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48911"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother. She reports that he has had shortness of breath and difficulty feeding since birth, which have progressively worsened. The child\u0027s lips and nose sometimes appear blue during breastfeeding. He has a medical history of Down syndrome. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly distressed. His pulse rate is 120/min, respiratory rate 40/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. On auscultation, a mid-diastolic rumbling murmur is heard at the lower left sternal border, along with a narrowly split S2 with a louder P2. The ECG shows a superior QRS axis shift, and there is a broad, notched P wave in leads II, III, and aVF. Chest X-ray reveals pulmonary plethora, cardiomegaly, and a left-sided aortic arch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tetralogy of Fallot","Transposition of the great arteries","Coarctation of aorta","Atrioventricular septal defect","Patent ductus arteriosus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation and findings on auscultation, ECG, and chest X-ray, the most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrioventricular septal defect (AVSD)\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as endocardial cushion defect. AVSD is a congenital heart defect that occurs due to incomplete fusion of the endocardial cushions during fetal development. It has a strong association with Down syndrome, and affected individuals often present with symptoms such as shortness of breath, difficulty feeding, and poor weight gain, as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic murmur of AVSD is a mid-diastolic rumbling murmur heard at the lower left sternal border, which may be accompanied by a narrowly split S2 with a louder P2 due to increased pulmonary artery pressure. The ECG findings typically show a superior QRS axis shift and a broad, notched P wave in leads II, III, and aVF. Chest X-ray may reveal cardiomegaly, pulmonary plethora, and a left-sided aortic arch, all of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital heart defect that involves four different anatomical abnormalities: ventricular septal defect (VSD), pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and overriding of aorta. While it can cause cyanosis and shortness of breath, the auscultation findings typically include a harsh systolic murmur, which is different from the mid-diastolic rumbling murmur heard in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransposition of the great arteries (TGA)\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital cardiac defect where the aorta and pulmonary artery are switched in position. While it can cause cyanosis and feeding difficulties, the auscultation findings are typically normal unless associated defects are present. The ECG and chest X-ray findings in this case are more consistent with AVSD than TGA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoarctation of the aorta\u003C/strong\u003E is a narrowing of the aorta, typically presenting with high blood pressure in the upper body, weak pulses in the lower body, and a harsh systolic murmur best heard in the back. The clinical presentation and examination findings in this case do not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatent ductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the ductus arteriosus fails to close after birth. It typically presents with a continuous \u0027machinery\u0027 murmur heard best below the left clavicle. The murmur description and other findings in this case are not consistent with PDA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Atrioventricular Septal Defect has a strong association with Down syndrome.","Atrioventricular Septal Defect typically presents with a mid-diastolic rumbling murmur at the lower left sternal border and a narrowly split S2 with a louder P2.","ECG findings in Atrioventricular Septal Defect often include a superior QRS axis shift and a broad, notched P wave in leads II, III, and aVF."],"references":["Ahmed I, Anjum F. Atrioventricular Septal Defect. [Updated 2022 Jul 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:16:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-18T08:24:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4984"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48911"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degre